 Delphi became a contested sacred site for Greeks and Romans and a storehouse for the treasures of rival city-states and foreign kings. He also examines the eventual decline of the site and how its meaning and importance have continued to be reshaped.A unique window into the center of the ancient world, Delphi will appeal to general readers, tourists, students, and specialists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aDelphian oraclexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400851324zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400851324.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  a978-3-11-066592-5  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN